05801nam a22009735i 9780823286843DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20202020nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232868437 a10.1515/97808232868432doi  a(DE-B1597)555274  a(OCoLC)1127275324  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aBH39b.G734 2020 7aLIT0041002bisacsh04a701.052231 aGraff Zivin, Erin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAnarchaeologies :bReading as Misreading /cErin Graff Zivin. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (192 p.) :b12  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLit Z00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: ethical and political thinking after literature -- tPart I. Anarchaeologies -- tMisunderstanding literature -- tToward an anarchaeological latinamericanism -- tPart II. The ethical turn -- tEthics against politics -- tLevinas in Latin America -- tPart III. Violent ethics -- tAbraham’s double bind -- tUntimely ethics: deconstruction and its precursors -- tPart IV. Political thinking after literature -- tThe metapolitics of allegory -- tThe aesthetics and politics of error -- tPart V. Exposure and indisciplinarity -- tToward a passive university -- tAfterword: Truth and error in the age of trump -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow do we read after the so-called death of literature? If we are to attend to the proclamations that the representational apparatuses of literature and politics are dead, what aesthetic, ethical, and political possibilities remain for us today? Our critical moment, Graff Zivin argues, demands anarchaeological reading: reading for the blind spots, errors, points of opacity or untranslatability in works of philosophy and art.Rather than applying concepts from philosophy in order to understand or elucidate cultural works, the book exposes works of philosophy, literary theory, narrative, poetry, film, and performance art and activism to one another. Working specifically with art, film, and literature from Argentina (Jorge Luis Borges, Juán José Saer, Ricardo Piglia, César Aira, Albertina Carri, the Internacional Errorista), Graff Zivin allows such thinkers as Levinas, Derrida, Badiou, and Rancière to be inflected by Latin American cultural production. Through these acts of interdiscursive and interdisciplinary (or indisciplinary) exposure, such ethical and political concepts as identification and recognition, decision and event, sovereignty and will, are read as constitutively impossible, erroneous. Rather than weakening either ethics or politics, however, the anarchaeological reading these works stage and demand opens up and radicalizes the possibility of justice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aArt and philosophy. 0aCriticism. 0aReadingxPhilosophy. 4aLatin American Studies. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aPhilosophy & Theory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Caribbean & Latin American.2bisacsh  aAlbertina Carri.  aArgentinian literature.  aCésar Aira.  aEmmanuel Levinas.  aJacques Derrida.  aJorge Luis Borges.  aLatin American studies.  aPaul de Man.  aRicardo Piglia.  acontinental philosophy.  adeconstruction.  aethics.  apolitics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishz978311070474708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area St